ents of our political responsibilities on topics such as residential schools, sweatshop labour, climate change, and forms of energy generation. Inspired by the final published writings of political and social theorist Iris Marion Young, specifically her outline of a “social connection model” of political responsibility, the contributors assess whether there are practices, policies, and institutions that could meaningfully address these expanded political responsibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aOppression (Psychology). 0aPolitical participation. 0aSocial justice. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBertoldi, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuji Johnson, Genevieve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnson, Genevieve Fuji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichaelis, Loralea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichaelis, Loralea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoore, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeer, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPritzlaff, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiff, J.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Melissa S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266576740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442665767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442665767.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  a